    "dataFlow": {
      "analogy": "Imagine walking into a huge store: you find a product on a shelf, drop it in your basket, take it to the register, the cashier checks your card, someone in the back confirms it is in stock and pulls it, and you walk out with a receipt while the store quietly updates its records. Online, the same trip happens in a couple of seconds, invisibly, for thousands of people at once.",
      "steps": [
        {
          "title": "Browse & search",
          "plain": "The shopper opens the store and searches or filters for a product; results and images appear almost instantly.",
          "detail": "Storefront request hits the CDN; cached product pages and images return from the edge. Search queries go to Elasticsearch/Algolia for ranked, faceted results; a recommendation call personalizes shelves from the shopper's session.",
          "time": "50–200 ms (edge cache hit)"
        },
        {
          "title": "Add to cart",
          "plain": "The shopper taps 'Add to cart'; the basket updates with the item, quantity, and running total.",
          "detail": "Cart service writes the line item to Redis-backed cart state keyed by session/customer, re-prices the cart, applies eligible promotions, and does a soft stock check against the inventory service's available-to-promise.",
          "time": "80–150 ms"
        },
        {
          "title": "Checkout & tax/shipping",
          "plain": "The shopper enters address and picks shipping; taxes and delivery cost are calculated and shown.",
          "detail": "Checkout service calls tax (Avalara/TaxJar) and shipping-rate providers, finalizes totals, and creates an idempotent checkout intent so a retry or double-click cannot create two orders.",
          "time": "200–500 ms"
        },
        {
          "title": "Payment authorization",
          "plain": "The shopper submits payment; the system securely verifies the card and confirms the money is good.",
          "detail": "Card is tokenized client-side and sent to the gateway (Stripe/Adyen). It runs fraud scoring and, if required, 3-D Secure/SCA challenge, then authorizes (and often captures) the amount. A webhook confirms the result asynchronously.",
          "time": "1–3 s (includes 3DS)"
        },
        {
          "title": "Order creation & stock reservation",
          "plain": "Payment approved — the store creates the order and sets aside your item so no one else can buy it.",
          "detail": "OMS starts the order saga: it commits the order record, the inventory service atomically decrements/reserves stock (distributed lock or event-sourced), and an order.created event is published to Kafka. If any step fails, the saga compensates (e.g., void the auth).",
          "time": "150–400 ms"
        },
        {
          "title": "Fulfillment & event fan-out",
          "plain": "The order is sent to the warehouse to pack and ship, and the shopper gets a confirmation email, while behind the scenes the numbers get updated.",
          "detail": "Consumers of the order event route fulfillment to a warehouse/3PL, trigger transactional email/SMS, update the search index and recommendations, and stream data to analytics, accounting, and the ERP — all asynchronously.",
          "time": "Async, ~seconds to minutes"
        }
      ],
      "failureHandling": [
        "Payment gateway timeout or decline: the checkout stays idempotent and the order is not created; the auth is voided and the shopper is prompted to retry or use another method, with webhook reconciliation catching late confirmations.",
        "Overselling / inventory race: reservations use atomic decrements or distributed locks, and the order saga rejects and compensates if stock cannot be secured, moving the item to backorder or notifying the shopper.",
        "Downstream service down (search, recs, email): these are decoupled via the event bus with retries and dead-letter queues, so browsing and checkout keep working even if recommendations or confirmation emails are delayed.",
        "Traffic spike (Black Friday): edge/CDN absorbs read traffic, autoscaling and rate limiting protect core services, and a queue/virtual waiting room smooths checkout load to prevent cascading failures."
      ]
    },
